# Architecture Philosophy

The app should evolve through:
- systems
- primitives
- reusable patterns
- centralized logic

Avoid:
- feature-by-feature chaos
- duplicated implementations
- isolated one-off fixes
- deeply nested dependencies
- hidden coupling

The app should behave:
like one coherent product platform.

---

# Refactor Decision Rules

Before refactoring:
1. Identify the actual structural problem
2. Trace duplication sources
3. Identify system ownership
4. Preserve current functionality
5. Improve extensibility
6. Minimize regression risk

Never refactor:
just because code “looks ugly.”

Refactor when:
- duplication increases
- features become fragile
- systems drift apart
- debugging becomes difficult
- scalability weakens
- feature velocity slows

---

# Component System Rules

Components should:
- have clear ownership
- remain reusable
- stay focused
- avoid hidden responsibilities

Avoid:
- giant multi-purpose components
- deeply nested render logic
- duplicated UI systems
- component-specific business logic everywhere

Prefer:
- composable primitives
- shared render systems
- isolated responsibility boundaries

---

# Report System Rules

All reports should share:
- common infrastructure
- shared rendering primitives
- centralized schemas
- theme systems
- reusable card pipelines

Avoid:
- fully isolated report implementations
- duplicated logic between report types
- report-specific hacks

The system should support:
future reports without architectural strain.

---

# Theme System Rules

Themes should remain:
- centralized
- extensible
- predictable
- reusable

Avoid:
- hardcoded colors
- duplicated gradients
- scattered typography overrides
- report-specific inline styles

Prefer:
- shared theme maps
- tokenized styling systems
- centralized visual definitions

---

# State Management Rules

State should remain:
- predictable
- traceable
- isolated
- minimal

Avoid:
- duplicated state
- prop drilling chaos
- hidden side effects
- deeply coupled state logic
- uncontrolled shared mutations

Prefer:
- normalized state ownership
- explicit data flow
- feature boundaries
- derived state when possible

---

# AI Pipeline Rules

AI orchestration should remain:
- modular
- debuggable
- cost-aware
- replaceable
- traceable

Avoid:
- prompt duplication
- giant monolithic prompts
- repeated preprocessing
- hardcoded model dependencies
- deeply coupled provider logic

Prefer:
- layered analysis pipelines
- reusable extraction stages
- modular prompts
- provider abstraction
- structured outputs

---

# Parsing Architecture Rules

Parsing systems should:
- remain modular per platform
- normalize into shared structures
- isolate preprocessing logic
- preserve debuggability

Avoid:
- parser spaghetti
- repeated transformations
- hidden cleanup stages
- platform-specific hacks scattered globally

---

# Motion & UI Architecture Rules

Animation systems should:
- use centralized timing/easing systems
- avoid duplicated motion logic
- remain visually consistent

UI systems should:
- use shared spacing
- shared typography
- shared layout primitives
- centralized visual tokens

Avoid:
